# AGENTS.md Template: Heartwood Memory for Codex

Paste this into the repository or user-level `AGENTS.md` that Codex reads after
you register the `heartwood` MCP server.

## Memory: use Heartwood as durable governed memory

An MCP server named `heartwood` provides governed, provenance-tracked memory.
Use it as the durable memory system of record.

- Before answering anything that depends on prior decisions, project conventions,
  user preferences, or resolved incidents, call `recall` with a natural-language
  cue. Treat returned `truth_status`, `provenance_valid`, and policy metadata as
  part of the context.
- When `remember` is enabled and you learn a durable fact, call `remember` with
  concise `content` and a stable `subject` such as the project, tenant, or user
  id. Set `classification` and `pii` honestly. Never store secrets, passwords,
  API keys, tokens, or private credential material.
- To explain why a memory was returned, call `explain_recall` with the
  `recall_id`.
- On an erasure request, call `forget` with the exact `subject`. If `forget` is
  not enabled in the MCP allowlist, stop and route the request to the operator.
- Do not treat local agent summaries as governed records. Heartwood is the
  auditable memory store for this workspace.
